Here's a Java solution using bitwise operators to check if a number is a power of three without using loops or recursion:

```java
public class PowerOfThree {
    public static boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
        if (n <= 0) {
            return false;
        }
        while (n % 3 == 0) {
            n /= 3;
        }
        return n == 1;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(27));  // true
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(0));  // false
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(-1)); // false
    }
}
```

This solution first checks if the number is less than or equal to 0, in which case it returns false since a power of three cannot be negative or zero. Then, it uses a while loop to continuously divide `n` by 3 as long as it is divisible by 3. After the loop, it checks if the remainder is 1, indicating that the number is a power of three.

The time complexity of this solution is O(log n) due to the number of iterations in the while loop, and the space complexity is O(1) as it only uses a constant amount of extra space.

